
[1]telegraph

   TEL'EGRAPH, n. [Gr. at a distance, and to write.] A machine for
   communicating intelligence from a distance by various signals or
   movements previously agreed on; which signals represent letters, words
   or ideas which can be transmitted form one station to another, as far
   as the signals can be seen. This machine was invented by the French
   about the year 1793 or 1794, and is now adopted by other nations.
     __________________________________________________________________

